ng person's mind is less vulnerable to suggestion, but it has not place in a public school. Young minds should be free of the bonds of religions, all religions, for if you let them in, in one instance they will enter into all areas of study sooner or later and the battle for religious supremacy will tear the system and its intent apart. How does a child study science when there religious background's view is that the world is only 6 thousand years old?! No, letting religion into public schools, even for a day is a bad move. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="837" language="en" documentId="1493" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Brendaat54" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/tempers-flare-over-prayer-in-schools-1.1104775" topic="prayer-in-schools" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="1493" notes="" title="Tempers flare over prayer in schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="837"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>